## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to apply STAR in a real production triage scenario, focusing on concrete observability, trade-offs between quick fixes and durable solutions, and clear stakeholder communication.

## Key Concepts

- STAR method disciplined storytelling
- Incident triage: observability, reproduction, isolation
- Risk/impact trade-offs: quick workaround vs permanent fix; rollback plans

## Code Example

```javascript
// Simple circuit breaker skeleton for a downstream call
function callWithCircuitBreaker(fn, timeout = 2000) {
  let open = false;
  let timer = null;
  return async function(...args) {
    if (open) throw new Error('Circuit open');
    try {
      const p = Promise.resolve(fn(...args));
      const r = await Promise.race([p, new Promise((_, reject) => setTimeout(() => reject(new Error('timeout')), timeout))]);
      timer && clearTimeout(timer);
      return r;
    } catch (e) {
      open = true;
      timer = setTimeout(() => { open = false; }, 3000);
      throw e;
    }
  };
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this plan for a high-traffic service with strict latency SLOs?
- What telemetry would you add to detect regressions early and prove the fix durable?
